.\" trim.1 – English man page for trim
.\" View with:  man ./trim.1
.\" Install:    sudo cp trim.1 /usr/local/share/man/man1/trim.1
.\"             sudo mandb
.TH TRIM 1 "2025" "trim 1.0" "User Commands"
.
.SH NAME
trim \- remove leading and trailing whitespace from each line
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B trim
.RI [ FILE .\|.\|.]
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B trim
reads each specified
.I FILE
line by line and removes leading and trailing whitespace characters
(spaces, tabs, and any other characters recognised by
.BR isspace (3))
from every line.
The result is written to
.IR stdout ;
each output line is terminated with a newline character (\en).
.PP
If no
.I FILE
is given, or if the only argument is
.BR \- ,
.B trim
reads from standard input
.RI ( stdin ).
.PP
.B trim
is designed to work well as a filter in shell pipelines, for example to
clean up the output of other commands or to normalise text files in bulk.
.
.SH OPTIONS
.B trim
currently accepts no options.
.
.SH EXAMPLES
Remove leading and trailing whitespace from a single string:
.PP
.RS
.EX
echo "   Hello World   " | trim
.EE
.RE
.PP
Output:
.PP
.RS
.EX
Hello World
.EE
.RE
.PP
Trim all lines in a text file:
.PP
.RS
.EX
trim essay.txt
.EE
.RE
.PP
Trim multiple files and write the result to a new file:
.PP
.RS
.EX
trim file1.txt file2.txt > result.txt
.EE
.RE
.PP
Use as a filter in a pipeline:
.PP
.RS
.EX
grep "keyword" data.txt | trim
.EE
.RE
.PP
.
.SH NOTES
.B trim
uses
.BR getline (3)
for line-by-line input, so arbitrarily long lines and large files are
handled correctly without fixed-size buffers.
.PP
Whitespace
.I within
a line (between words) is left unchanged.
.PP
Characters considered whitespace are those recognised by
.BR isspace (3):
space (0x20), horizontal tab (\\t), newline (\\n), carriage return (\\r),
form feed (\\f), and vertical tab (\\v).
.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR sed (1),
.BR awk (1),
.BR xargs (1),
.BR isspace (3),
.BR getline (3)
.
.SH AUTHOR
Christian Forler
